    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Aquilaria parvifolia improperly include develop skin irritation due to the presence of sesquiterpenes and coumarins, which can cause allergic reactions and skin inflammation, leading to redness, itching and rashes. Ingesting Aquilaria parvifolia can also increase blood pressure and induce nausea due to the presence of alkaloids and other bioactive compounds that can stimulate the nervous system and cause gastrointestinal discomfort. Furthermore, using Aquilaria parvifolia improperly can also experience allergic reactions, such as anaphylaxis, in sensitive individuals due to the presence of allergenic compounds like sesquiterpenes and flavonoids. The improper use of Aquilaria parvifolia can also cause respiratory problems, such as asthma and bronchitis, due to the release of volatile organic compounds that can irritate the airways. These side effects are caused by the improper extraction and use of Aquilaria parvifolia, which can lead to the accumulation of toxic compounds in the body.",
    "uses": "Aquilaria parvifolia is known for its potential medicinal properties, primarily in traditional medicine. The plant is used to treat various health issues, including fever, headache, and digestive problems. Its extracts are said to possess antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties, which can help in treating wounds and reducing inflammation. The plant's bark and leaves are used to make tea, which is believed to have antioxidant and detoxifying effects. However, more research is needed to fully understand and validate its medicinal uses.",
    "taxonomy": "Aquilaria parvifolia is classified as a species within the genus Aquilaria and the family Thymelaeaceae. It belongs to the order Thymelaeales and the clade Rosidae. The plant is native to the tropical regions of Asia, and its classification is often grouped under the broader category of 'agarwood trees'. The precise classification of Aquilaria parvifolia is still subject to ongoing research and scientific updates. This species is often listed under the family Thymelaeaceae, which comprises about 40 species of trees and shrubs.",
    "benefits": "Aquilaria parvifolia, also known as small-leaved eaglewood, has been studied for its potential health benefits. It is said to possess antimicrobial properties, which may help in reducing inflammation and promoting wound healing. The plant's essential oil may also exhibit antifungal and antibacterial activities, making it a potential natural remedy for various infections. Additionally, Aquilaria parvifolia contains sesquiterpenes, which may have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects. Further research is needed to confirm the plant's efficacy and safety as a medicinal agent.",
    "parts": "Aquilaria parvifolia, a plant species native to Southeast Asia, is used in traditional medicine, particularly for its antiseptic and anti-inflammatory properties. The medicinal parts of Aquilaria parvifolia are its bark, leaves, and roots, which are used to treat various health conditions. The plant's extracts have been used to treat wounds, skin infections, and fever. In traditional medicine, Aquilaria parvifolia is also used to treat digestive issues and respiratory problems. The plant's antiseptic properties make it a valuable resource in treating infections and promoting wound healing.",
    "intro": "Aquilaria parvifolia, also known as the small-leaf agarwood, is a plant species native to Asia, belonging to the Thymelaeaceae family. This plant is valued for its health benefits, which include anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, and antioxidant properties, making it effective in treating various ailments such as fever, cough, and skin conditions. The bioactive constituents of Aquilaria parvifolia include limonoids, flavonoids, and sesquiterpenes, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. The most common herbal preparations made from this plant include decoctions, infusions, and essential oils, which are used in traditional medicine to treat various health conditions."
